body:
In vpi_iterate, there's no case for vpiInternalScope which I believe is the way we should be accessing scopes within a generate block. Currently, it's possible to get them by name, but within a module I want to be able to get a handle to the namespaces for generate blocks and use that again to get other attributes.

To adapt an example in t_vpi_var.v if we have
```   
module t ...;
   ...
   genvar i;
   generate begin : gen_loop
   for (i=1; i<=6; i=i+1) begin : arr
     arr #(.LENGTH(i)) arr();
   end
   end endgenerate

endmodule : t
```
According to my readings of 37.83 and 37.5 in IEEE1800, I believe it should work like the following in c++:
```
   gen_loop_h = vpi_iterate(vpiInternalScope, module_h);
   gen_loop_gen_arr_h = vpi_iterate(vpiInternalScope, gen_loop_h);
   gen_loop_gen_arr_0_h = vpi_handle_by_index(gen_loop_gen_arr_h, 0);
   gen_loop_gen_arr_0_arra_h = vpi_iterate(vpiInternalScope, gen_loop_gen_arr_0_h);
```

I think the solution here would be to have the generate block identifier be a scope that somehow keeps track of its child scopes, but I'm open to ideas on how to get this working.
